                <note rend="inline" type="source">551.5F1/23: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-02-18T13:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 18, 1931—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>57. After lengthy deliberation aside from the pending Pittman report, the
                    Department on February 16 requested Dawes in London to learn the attitude of the
                    Government there with regard to its sponsorship of an international conference
                    on silver. I have two reasons for suggesting that the initiative be taken by the
                    British Government: (1) silver is not being sold by the United States and its
                    silver coinage is not being debased; (2) the price of silver is determined on
                    the London market.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
